The '''Tuvalu Association of Sports and National Olympic Committee''' (TASNOC) is the Tuvaluan organization recognized as a National Olympic Committee (NOC) by the [[International Olympic Committee|International Olympic Committee (IOC)]].  In 2006, [[Tuvalu]] satisfied the IOC's criterion of a minimum five national sports federations recognized by their international sports federations, which included [[Basketball in Tuvalu|basketball]], volleyball, [[Tuvalu Weightlifting Federation|weightlifting]], boxing and table tennis.<ref name="Diana Semi and Silafaga Lalua">{{cite web|first=|last=Diana Semi and Silafaga Lalua|title=400 grand needed for TAS|date=2 November 2006|url=http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2006/11/400_grand_needed_for_tas.html|accessdate=3 May 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018180556/http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2006/11/400_grand_needed_for_tas.html|archivedate=18 October 2012|df=}}</ref>   

TASNOC is a signatory to the World Anti-Doping Code published by the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]].<ref name="WADA">{{cite web| last =| first =| work =World Anti-Doping Agency| title =Code Signatories| date =2016| url =https://www.wada-ama.org/en/code-signatories| accessdate =20 March 2016| deadurl =no| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20160309215004/https://www.wada-ama.org/en/code-signatories| archivedate =9 March 2016| df =}}</ref>

==History ==
TASNOC came into existence when the ''Tuvalu Amateur Sport Association'' or ''Tuvalu Association of Sports'' (TAS) was recognized as the ''Tuvalu National Olympic Committee'' on 16 July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|first=Silafaga |last=Lalua |title=Tuvalu in the IOC |date=9 July 2007 |url=http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2007/07/tuvalu_in_the_ioc.html |publisher=Tuvalu-News.TV |accessdate=3 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018181007/http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2007/07/tuvalu_in_the_ioc.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> 
Robert Laupula managed the Tuvalu Sports Association and the application for membership of the Olympic movement, which was co-ordinated by the [[Oceania National Olympic Committees]].<ref name="Diana Semi and Silafaga Lalua"/><ref>{{cite web |first= Diana |last= Semi |title= Tuvaluan doing very well in weightlifting |date= 1 November 2006 |url= http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2006/11/tuvaluan_doing_very_well_in_we.html |accessdate= 3 May 2014 |deadurl= no |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121018180559/http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2006/11/tuvaluan_doing_very_well_in_we.html |archivedate= 18 October 2012 |df=  }}</ref>

[[Geoffrey Ludbrook]], who represented Tuvalu at the [[Tuvalu at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne]] in the men's 50m Rifle Prone event, worked with the [[Oceania Shooting Federation]]  so that the Tuvalu Shooting Association obtained full membership of the  International Shooting Sport Federation (ISSF) in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Executive Meeting Oceania Shooting Federation: Minutes B.07.13 Tuvalu|date=2007|url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-1602-0-0-0&sID=14422&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=4667902|accessdate=3 May 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503220445/http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-1602-0-0-0&sID=14422&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=4667902|archivedate=3 May 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Tuvalu Shooting Federation  - ISSF Membership|date=2007|url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-1602-0-0-0&sID=14422&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5520311|accessdate=3 May 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503220447/http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-1602-0-0-0&sID=14422&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5520311|archivedate=3 May 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Oceania Shooting Federation - OSF|date=2013|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/theissf/championships/continental_championships/oceania.ashx|accessdate=3 May 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503152134/http://www.issf-sports.org/theissf/championships/continental_championships/oceania.ashx|archivedate=3 May 2014|df=}}</ref>

In 2013, Tuvalu was granted Associate status in the [[Oceania Continent Handball Federation]] by the [[International Handball Federation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ihf.info//TheIHF//ContinentalFederations//OceaniaHandballFederation(OHF)//ListofFederations//TuvaluHandballAssociation|title=Tuvalu Handball Association|publisher=International Handball Federation|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref>

==Facilities and management==

Tuvalu has one sporting field close to the airport. Athletes also train on the airport tarmac, the beach, or on a road. TASNOC's Secretary General said the following about the biggest challenges the committee faces: "I think it’s finance and facilities, sporting facilities."<ref name="HS16" />

The athletes do not have access to nutritionists, physiotherapists, and sports psychologists. They talk with the pastors of the church for guidance.<ref name="HS16" />

In 2007 the Secretary General of the Tuvalu National Olympic Committee was Nakibae Kitiseni.<ref>{{cite web|first=Silafaga |last=Lalua |title=Tuvalu in the IOC |date=9 July 2007 |url=http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2007/07/tuvalu_in_the_ioc.html |publisher=Tuvalu-News.TV |accessdate=31 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018181007/http://www.tuvalu-news.tv/archives/2007/07/tuvalu_in_the_ioc.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 |df= }}</ref> The Secretary General in 2012 was Teake Esene Manatu,<ref name="Fox12">{{cite web | work=foxsportspulse.com | title=Team Tuvalu Sprinting Home | date=4 August 2012 | url=http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-3862-0-0-0&sID=254093&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=20160332 | accessdate=3 May 2014 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503220442/http://www.foxsportspulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=2-3862-0-0-0&sID=254093&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=20160332 | archivedate=3 May 2014 | df= }}</ref> who was succeeded by Isala T. Isala on April 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=IOC|title=Tuvalu|url=http://www.olympic.org/tuvalu|accessdate=9 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210095449/http://www.olympic.org/tuvalu|archivedate=10 December 2011|df=}}</ref><ref name="anoc">{{cite web|url=http://www.anocolympic.org/nocs-directory/tuvalu-association-of-sports-and-national-olympic-committee/16701|title=Secretary General|publisher=ANOC|access-date=November 7, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108094636/http://www.anocolympic.org/nocs-directory/tuvalu-association-of-sports-and-national-olympic-committee/16701|archivedate=November 8, 2017|df=}}</ref> The Secretary General is responsible for the logistics of the Tuvalu Games, as well as the logistics when athletes participate in regional and international competitions. They are also in charge of talent acquisition and recruiting.<ref name="HS16" />

Kausea Natano was TASNOC's President in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuvaluislands.com/news/archived/2007/2007-07-06.htm|title=Tuvalu Joins Olympic Committee|date=July 6, 2007|access-date=November 7, 2017|publisher=Tuvalu Online|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008104013/http://www.tuvaluislands.com/news/archived/2007/2007-07-06.htm|archivedate=October 8, 2014|df=}}</ref> Ampelosa  Tehulu, from the Tuvalu Basketball Sports Federation, was elected President of TASNOC on 5 March 2015.<ref name="FNS0315">{{cite web | last =Taumaheke | first =Kuata | work =Fenui News | title =TASNOC is under new leadership | date =9 March 2015 | url =https://www.un.int/tuvalu/sites/www.un.int/files/Tuvalu/Documents/GA/fenui_mar_09_2015.pdf | accessdate =12 June 2015 | deadurl =no | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150621083430/https://www.un.int/tuvalu/sites/www.un.int/files/Tuvalu/Documents/GA/fenui_mar_09_2015.pdf | archivedate =21 June 2015 | df = }}</ref>  [[Eselealofa Apinelu]] was the immediate past President.<ref name="TASNOC">{{cite web| last =| first =| title =Directory 2013| publisher =Pacific Games Council| date =2013| url =http://www.athletics-oceania.com/fileadmin/user_upload/Directory/2013_PGC_Directory.pdf| accessdate =24 May 2015| deadurl =yes| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201624/http://www.athletics-oceania.com/fileadmin/user_upload/Directory/2013_PGC_Directory.pdf| archivedate =4 March 2016| df =}}</ref> Iakopo Molotii was elected President of TASNOC on September 9, 2016.<ref name="anoc" />

The annual budget of TASNOC is 10,000 Australian dollars.<ref name="HS16">{{cite web|first=Alexandros|last=Tsathas|work=Honi Soit|title=In the running|date=2 August 2016|url=http://honisoit.com/2016/08/in-the-running/|accessdate=5 August 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803225654/http://honisoit.com/2016/08/in-the-running/|archivedate=3 August 2016|df=}}</ref>

==Events==
===Olympics===
{{Main|Tuvalu at the Olympics}}
[[Tuvalu]] participates in the [[Olympic Games]] in the [[Summer Olympics]] and have not competed at the [[Winter Olympics|Winter Games]].<ref>{{cite web|last=IOC|title=Tuvalu|url=http://www.olympic.org/tuvalu|accessdate=9 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210095449/http://www.olympic.org/tuvalu|archivedate=10 December 2011|df=}}</ref> Tuvalu entered the Olympic Games for the first time at the [[Tuvalu at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Games]] in [[Beijing]], China, with a weightlifter and two athletes in the men's and women's 100-metre sprints. A team with athletes in the same events represented [[Tuvalu at the 2012 Summer Olympics]], in [[London]], United Kingdom.<ref name="TPB 2812">{{cite web | work=London 2012 – Tuvalu in the 30th Olympiad of the Modern Era | title=Tuvalu Philatelic Bureau Newsletter (TPB: 02/2012) | date=7 August 2012 | url=http://stampsoftuvalu.com/ | accessdate=3 May 2014 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330024756/http://www.stampsoftuvalu.com/ | archivedate=30 March 2013 | df= }}</ref> [[Etimoni Timuani]] represented Tuvalu at [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in the 100 metre event, making Tuvalu the only country to send one competitor to the 2016 Olympic Games.<ref name=rio>[https://www.rio2016.com/en/athlete/etimoni-timuani Etimoni Timuani] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802181747/https://www.rio2016.com/en/athlete/etimoni-timuani |date=2016-08-02 }}. rio2016.com</ref><ref name="RS16">{{cite web| work=Rolling Stone| title=The Underdogs: 15 Olympic Athletes That Could Shock the World| date=5 August 2016| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/pictures/15-olympic-athletes-that-could-shock-the-world-w432770/etimoni-timuani-w432836| accessdate=5 August 2016| deadurl=no| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819165400/http://www.rollingstone.com/sports/pictures/15-olympic-athletes-that-could-shock-the-world-w432770/etimoni-timuani-w432836| archivedate=19 August 2016| df=}}</ref>

===Pacific Games===
{{Main|Tuvalu at the Pacific Games}}
TASNOC organizes Tuvalu's participation in the [[Pacific Games]], and they have participated in six Games. The association is responsible for training the athletes and preparation for the Games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.int/tuvalu/sites/www.un.int/files/Tuvalu/Documents/GA/fenui_feb_02_2015.pdf|title=TASNOC named Deputy CDM and Team Manager for Pacific Games 2015|date=February 2, 2015|access-date=January 20, 2018|publisher=Fenui}}</ref> Tuvalu arrived at the 2015 Pacific Games two hours before the Opening Ceremony due to a cyclone that affected the team's travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1028412/tuvalu-set-to-arrive-at-pacific-games-just-two-hours-before-opening-ceremony-due-to-weather-hit-journey|title=Tuvalu set to arrive at Pacific Games just two hours before Opening Ceremony due to weather-hit journey|last1=Morgan|first1=Liam|publisher=Inside the Games|access-date=January 20, 2018|date=July 2, 2015}}</ref> They earned their first ever gold medal at the games when [[Telupe Iosefa]] won the powerlifting competition.<ref name="IG1">{{cite web| last =Morgan  | first =Liam   | work= Pacific Games 2015|title= Tuvalu claim first-ever Pacific Games gold medal as Samoa and Nauru share Port Moresby 2015 powerlifting spoils|date =10 July 2015 |url= http://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1028592/tuvalu-claim-first-ever-pacific-games-gold-medal-as-samoa-and-nauru-share-port-moresby-2015-powerlifting-spoils| accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>

==Tuvalu Commonwealth Games Association==
{{Main|Tuvalu at the Commonwealth Games}}
TASNOC is also responsible for organising Tuvalu’s participation in the [[Commonwealth Games]] and the [[Commonwealth Youth Games]]. Tuvalu joined the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] and first participated in the [[1998 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games in 1998]], when a weightlifter attended the games held at Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.<ref name="CGF - Tuvalu"/> [[Tuvalu]] has subsequently sent teams to compete in every [[Commonwealth Games]] since 2002. As of the 2014 Games, Tuvalu has not won a medal. They have participated in table tennis, athletics, shooting, and weightlifting.<ref name="CGF - Tuvalu">{{cite web|first=|last=|title=CGF - Tuvalu|date=|url=http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=TUV|publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation|accessdate=15 May 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070729025928/http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=TUV|archivedate=29 July 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

